					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/rigen" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2826105); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2826105&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226158" alt="Rigen" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2826105)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/rigen" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2826105); return false;" >Rigen</a></span> <span class="odate time_1542325120 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">15 Nov 2018 23:38</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4059746">
									

<p>The introductory text is rather bland, imo. It's just repeating the &quot;we're religious yay yay infidels die&quot; spiel that we're fed in media (at least my nation's media) everyday. It doesn't really explain much &#8212; it doesn't even explain what groups formed the HI, whose God are we talking about. It also mentioned that they unite under the banner of God, but doesn't really explain how they overcame their differences and unite under their holy banner. We're talking millennia-old religious groups here.</p>
<p>Seconding drblackbox that it needs to be more clear about who are HI and what they <em>do.</em> I don't have as much distaste for preachy language, but even mosques and churches have official letter and documents that are formatted systematically. I reckon indoctrination into faith and ideology would be done through actual training, while official documents would be more to the point. Taking notes from ORIA and/or GOC hubs would probably help a bunch.</p>

							</div>

								
					
